rkshire, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1283–1310":"1283–1310","1278–1348":"1278–1348","1305–1400":"1305–1400","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1307–Male":"1307–Deceased","1309–Male":"1309–Deceased","1263–Male":"1263–Deceased","ABT 1309":"about 1309","1263":"1263","1283":"1283","ABT 1305":"about 1305","ABT 1307":"about 1307","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1400":"1400","1278":"1278","1310":"1310","about 1304":"about 1304","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","of North Denchworth, Berkshire, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","North Denchworth, Berks, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Denchworth, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, England","Bocland, Berkshire, England":"Buckland, Berkshire, England","Denchworth, Berkshire, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bocland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Boland   1 and 2.","English: variant of   Bolland   2.","Americanized form of German <b>Bauland</b>: topographic name for someone who lived by land that was under cultivation."],"variants":[{"name":"Boland","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Bridie, Caitlin, Donal, Finbar, Maeve.","English: habitational name from the district of Bowland (Forest) in North Yorkshire and Lancashire. Robert <i>of Bowland</i> was a member of the garrison of Stirling castle in Scotland in 1339–40, and was presumably a Yorkshireman or a Lancastrian.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beólláin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beóllán</i>’, an old Irish name of uncertain origin. See   Bolan   1."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":7,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Bocland was born in 1283, in Buckland, Berkshire, England as the daughter of Walter Bocland. She married Almeric Fettiplace about 1304, in Berkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1310, in Denchworth, Berkshire, England, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1283–1310":"1283–1310","1278–1348":"1278–1348","1305–1400":"1305–1400","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1307–Male":"1307–Surnud","1309–Male":"1309–Surnud","1263–Male":"1263–Surnud","ABT 1309":"umbes 1309","1263":"1263","1283":"1283","ABT 1305":"umbes 1305","ABT 1307":"umbes 1307","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1400":"1400","1278":"1278","1310":"1310","about 1304":"umbes 1304","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","of North Denchworth, Berkshire, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Denchworth, Berks, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Denchworth, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, England","Bocland, Berkshire, England":"Buckland, Berkshire, England","Denchworth, Berkshire, England":"Denchworth, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1283–1310":"1283–1310","1278–1348":"1278–1348","1305–1400":"1305–1400","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1307–Male":"1307–Kuollut","1309–Male":"1309–Kuollut","1263–Male":"1263–Kuollut","ABT 1309":"noin 1309","1263":"1263","1283":"1283","ABT 1305":"noin 1305","ABT 1307":"noin 1307","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1400":"1400","1278":"1278","1310":"1310","about 1304":"noin 1304","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","of North Denchworth, Berkshire, E